16-0A1CCC6F451C"><gtr:id>DD21C8A9-95D9-4867-9416-0A1CCC6F451C</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Pia</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Riggirozzi</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE005594%2F1"><gtr:id>5DA91F5E-C6BC-4FD9-AFB0-8DBDFE4A1189</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Role of the World Bank in the Reconstruction of Governance in Argentina</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E005594/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The research focuses on the role of the World Bank in post-crisis governance reforms in Argentina. It argues that when the World Bank is able to draw on its financial and knowledge power to consolidate pro-reform networks with local actors it is more likely to ensure the implementation of governance reforms in its client countries. This claim builds on the premise that the dominance of a particular actor or paradigm vis-a-vis other contending actors or ideas is not reinforced simply by the coercive position of the lender, but rather by its capacity to integrate contesting impulses into broader consensus for policy change. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The study provides an analysis on the relation between power, knowledge and policy processes involving international agencies and developing countries; and on patterns of involvement of the World Bank in politically sensitive reforms. The approach departs from the existing literature that tends to consider the World Bank as a uniform actor disseminating funds and knowledge, and that its paradigms are a-critically taken up in developing countries. Findings show that policy outcomes differ according to whether the World Bank acts either as 'conveyor' of funds and knowledge or as a ?norm-broker? engaging with local actors in policy reforms.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-08-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>76165</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>8D19A8F7-E48C-4272-90B7-B2C8A6FF5421</gtr:id><gtr:title>Advancing Governance in the South: What Roles for International Financial Institutions in Developing States?: 2009</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/4fa351d9f9f2eb8da67f79b3b92b3516"><gtr:id>4fa351d9f9f2eb8da67f79b3b92b3516</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Riggirozzi Pia</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2008-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>9780230220119</gtr:isbn><gtr:outcomeId>i_59556272033b810458<